Introduction to allergy 

Thursday, May 11, 2017 

2:32 PM 

Define allergy and atopy 

An allergic reaction is a hypersensitive reaction of the immune system to harmless antigens (environmental factors). An allergen is an innocuous antigen, and includes food allergens (wheat/dairy), or inhaled allergens (house dust-mites, pollens). Atopy is the genetic tendency to develop allergic diseases.  

 

Briefly describe the four types of hypersensitivity 

Type 1: Immediate/within minutes, contact hypersensitivity, can be either systemic (life-endangering anaphylaxis), or local (food or nasal allergy, asthma). This is provoked by re-exposure to the same antigen by contact, inhalation, ingestion or injection.  

 

-Primary mediators (preformed, participates in initial response): biogenic amines eg histamine and adenosine, chemotactic mediators, enzymes, proteoglycans 

-Secondary mediators (requires synthesis, participates in late-phase reaction): Leukotrienes (LTC4), Prostaglandin D2, PAF, Cytokines (TNFa, IL-1, IL-3, IL-4, IL-5, IL-6) 

 

Type 2: The antibodies produced by the immune response bind to antigens on the patient's own cell surfaces. This involves antibody-complement-mediated lysis. Some drug allergies are Type 2, eg penicillin allergies.  

Antibody (IgM or IgG) + antigen on cell surface = opsonized cell, leading to the activation of the complement system and then macrophage phagocytosis.  

 

Type 3: Humoral antibodies (IgG) bind blood-born antigens and form insoluble antigen-antibody complexes in circulation. This activates complement pathways that leads to cell damage in blood vessels and tissue where complexes are deposited. Type 3 hypersensitivity can occur with bacteria, viruses, parasites, fungi, nuclear antigens, immunoglobulins, and tumor antigens. Arthritis is a major clinical manifestation arising from this.  

 

Type 4: This is cell-mediated (T-lymphocytes, CD8+ or CD4+) hypersensitivity, (not antibody-mediated), and is in response to large insoluble antigens. This occurs in viral clearance, autoimmune disease and host vs graft transplant rejection.  

 

 

Create a simple diagram of the interacting components and mechanisms involved in allergen-induced inflammation (include antigen/allergen, dendritic cells, Th2 cells, B cells, IgE, mast cells and important cytokines) 

 

Identify the points on the diagram above where anti-inflammatory medications could potentially interfere 

 

Antihistamines targeting the histamine H1 receptors in mast cells, smooth muscle and the endothelium are used to treat allergic reactions in the nose and for insomnia, whilst those targeting the H2 receptors in the upper GI tract are used to treat gastric acid conditions. 

 

Mast cell stabilisers block a calcium channel to reduce intracellular calcium, preventing the fusing of histamine vesicles to the cell membrane. Thus, mast cell degranulation does not occur and histamine is not released. 

 

Leukotriene modifiers prevent the action of leukotrienes (via antagonism), which are released by mast cells during a Th2 or allergic response.  

 

Steroid-based anti-inflammatory drugs bind to glucocorticoid receptor and suppress expression of many genes causing inflammation.  

 

Using asthma as an example, describe the allergic mechanisms that lead to disease 

-Children who are prone to allergy can often develop further allergies throughout their childhood, with overlapping symptoms 

-Early-life allergic sensitisation to atopic dermatitis, food, and cigarette smoke allergens increase the risk of asthma development.  

 

Type-2 immunity underpins allergic inflammation in asthma. Airway epithelium responds to exposure to allergen and releases mediators that activate Th2 cells which cause bronchial hyperreactivity to spasmogens. Th2 cells furthermore produce type 2 cytokines activating mast cells, B cells, innate lymphoid cells, and cause airway narrowing and mucus production.
